(4, 0, '2013-06-14 07:03:32', '', '', 0, '<div> <p><img src="images/glance.png" alt="Jakin at a glance"></p>\r\n        <p><img src="images/glance2.png" alt="Jakin at a glance 2"></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div>', '1014', 5, 'Jakin-At-a-Glance', '', '0'),
(6, 0, '2013-06-14 07:37:48', '', '', 0, ' <p><strong>EXTERNALLY FUNDED PROJECTS</strong>: - these projects are initiated and sponsored by the following - NGO&rsquo;s, Private and Government institutions, churches, local or International funders.</p>\r\n        \r\n        <h6> The Enhancing Nigeria&rsquo;s Response to HIV/AIDS (ENR)</h6>\r\n        <p>The Enhancing Nigeria&rsquo;s Response to HIV/AIDS (ENR) six-year programme funded by the United Kingdom Aid (UKaid) commenced in 2010 to improve access to and coverage of effective HIV and AIDS prevention, treatment, care and support information and services reaching the most vulnerable population. </p>\r\n        <p>The programme involves an eight-partner consortium (Society for Family Health, ActionAid Nigeria, Options, Benguela, BBC World Service Trust, Population Services International, Population Council and Crown Agent).\r\n          \r\n         JAKIN N.G.O implemented PEP and PLACE projects under the ENR grant. </p>\r\n        <p>The 6 months <strong><em>Peer Education Plus strategy (PEP)</em></strong> implemented at Orile Iganmu (Ibile) division Lagos state established 40 HIV/AIDS peer education groups among Female out of School Youths, Male Out of School Youths, Transport workers and Female Sex workers.         </p>\r\n        <p>For the <strong><em>Priority Local Aids Control Effort strategy (PLACE</em></strong>) implementation, SABO, ALAGOMEJI and IWAYA communities of Mainland Local Government were selected as the three priority prevention areas (PPA&rsquo;s). 15 venues (Hot spots i.e bars and night clubs) were selected and 30 venue outreach staffs (VOS) were extensively trained and engaged for the 6 months project. 19,879 people were reached, 5,060 condoms distributed, 1,979 people were referred for HIV Counseling and testing, 1,069 were referred for Sexually Transmitted Infection (STI) treatment and 321 were referred for Family Planning. </li>\r\n          \r\n          Under the project media component - BBC Media Action, Jakin N.G.O was engaged to <strong><em>monitor two HIV/Aids enlightenment radio programs</em></strong> on UNILAG FM from November 2012  April 2013</li>\r\n        </p>\r\n        <h6>Annual world aids day </h6>\r\n          \r\n        \r\n        <p>To commemorate the annual World Aids Day celebration, Jakin for the past 3 years organized HIVAIDS enlightenment seminars to traditional birth attendants, community volunteers in Yaba and Makoko areas. </p>\r\n        <p>Jakin has also conducted HCT services and Road shows with IEC material distributed within less privileged communities.</p>\r\n        <h6>Global Fund/ARFH/AONN OVC Cluster project</h6>\r\n        <p>In 2011, as the lead CBO for Mainland and Lagos Island LG for the OVC Cluster project funded by Global Fund through the Association for Reproductive Family Health (ARFH) in collaboration with the Association for orphans and vulnerable children in Nigeria (AONN), 31 Orphans and Vulnerable Children were selected and have been served with educational, health and nutritional support packages. Jakin also set up a Child Protection Committee in the Cluster site.</p>\r\n        <h6>Society for Family Health (SFH) Global Fund Malaria Round 8/AMFm project  free RDT/ACTand community social mobilization</h6>\r\n        <p>In 2011, Jakin conducted free Malaria Rapid Diagnosis testing (RDT) funded by Global fund through Society for Family Health (SFH) Global Fund Malaria Round 8/AMFm project in 92 communities in Mainland and 37 communities in Somolu Local Government areas.</p>\r\n        <p>16,644 community members were tested in Yaba - and Somolu LCDA, 503 people tested positive and 55 were given Anti-malaria combination therapy (ACT) drugs while others were referred for further treatment at primary health centres. Also 1,665 people were reached with knowledge of Malaria prevention, causes and treatment during community social mobilization using playlet and town crying in 27 communities.</p>\r\n        <h6>Ukaid/ National Malaria Program (SUNMAP) -LLIN and SP monitoring in health facilities </h6>\r\n        <p>In June 2011, Jakin conducted a one week rapid monitoring of LLIN and SPs - Sulphadoxine Pyrimethamine in 9 Government health facilities in Mainland LG under the Lagos State Ministry of Health. Support was from Ukaid- Support to National Malaria Program (SUNMAP).</p>\r\n        <h6>Global fund/HAF Community Tuberculosis Control (CTBC) project</h6>\r\n        <p>On Community Tuberculosis Control (CTBC) project, which is funded by Global Fund through Health Alive Foundation (HAF) in 2011, Jakin was selected as the Mainland LG lead CBO. <br>\r\n          <br>\r\n         10 Community volunteers were trained for the project, as at June 2013 , 246 TB suspects were referred for DOTS and 21 are receiving treatment.</p>\r\n        <h6>USaid/Fhi Integrated Community based TB care project</h6>\r\n        <p>In August - December, 2011, Jakin was selected through an assessment by Family Health International (FHI) team to implement the USAID funded Integrated Community based TB care component of TB prevention within Iwaya and Oko Agbon communities of Mainland Local Government. <br>\r\n          <br>\r\n         5 community Volunteers were trained for the project, so far 49 TB suspects have been referred for DOTS and 4 are receiving treatment while 6 community social mobilizations were conducted.</p>\r\n        <h6>LACSOP - priority health needs assessment </h6>\r\n        <p>Jakin also conducted a seven days focus group discussion for five groups on priority health needs assessment in Ikorodu local Government organized by LACSOP  Lagos State Civil society Partnership in October 2011.</p>\r\n        <h6>WHO/Lagos State Government - free LLIN distribution </h6>\r\n        <p>In September, 2011, 2000 free Long Lasting Insecticide mosquito nets provided by WHO was distributed in Jakin N.G.O for community members of Yaba LCDA through Lagos State Government. </p>\r\n        <h6>SHI malaria role model caregivers training</h6>\r\n        <p>Ten eligible community volunteers were selected to be trained as Malaria Role Model Care givers in Mainland local Government. The training organized by JAKIN N.G.O under the Sustainable Health Initiative (Shi) Priority strategy is focused on familiarizing participants with the project and equipping them with knowledge on malaria causes, prevention, treatment, care and support. The objective of the training is to build participant&rsquo;s skill, as role model care givers on effective case handling of malaria in the community under the Mainland local Government.</p>\r\n        <h6>USAID/FHI-360 community tuberculosis care (CTBC) project </h6>\r\n        <p>On Community Tuberculosis care (CTBC) project, which is funded by USAID through Family Health International (FHi-360) in 2012, Jakin was selected as the CBO to work in Lagos Mainland LG as a collaborating CBO. From 2012- 2013, 25 Community Volunteers have being trained on causes and cure of Tuberculosis and methodology for community entry for TB program.<br>\r\n         </p>\r\n        <p>714 TB suspects have been referred so far for TB diagnosis at DOTs Center, 102 TB patients are receiving treatment and 102 Patient are on receiving treatment support by 25 CVs working as a treatment supporter.</p>\r\n        <h6>USAID/FHI-360 strengthening integrated delivery of HIV/AIDS services (SIDHAS) project</h6>\r\n        <p>Under the FHi-360 USAID funded 5 years Strengthening integrated delivery of HIV/Aids services<strong> </strong>(SIDHAS) which commenced in April 2012, Humanity Family Foundation for Peace and Development, Ikorodu is collaborating with Jakin N.G.O for implementation in Mainland L.G. <br>\r\n         Jakin N.G.O is implementing the HIV/Aids prevention among most at risk population MARPS (commercial sex workers and transport workers) component in the L.G.</p>\r\n        <p>4 persons have been trained as counselor testers for HIV counseling and testing (HCT), and 3 peer educators trained to reach MARPS with HIV prevention messages. So far 60 transport workers and 124 commercial sex workers have reached with HIV prevention messages. 137 persons have been reached with HCT with 3 referred for treatment and 40 referred for STI. A blood donation drive was also conducted Iwaya and Makoko communities. a community dialogue reaching 31 community members was conducted on HIV/Aids stigma and discrimination in Pedro and Ago- egun communities. A community mobilization was conducted on HCT, Prevention of Mother to child transmission (PMTCT) and Non communicable diseases (NCDs).</p>\r\n        <h6>CDC/FHI Ahni SCHARP Project - care and support for VC</h6>\r\n        <p>In September -2012, Jakin collaborated with FHI Ahni (Achieving Heath Nigeria Initiative) to provide health, legal protection (birth certificate) and nutritional support services for 600 vulnerable children in Mainland LG under the CDC  Centre for Disease Control funded SCHARP Project. </p>\r\n        <p>A kids club was also established and conducted for the children.</p>\r\n        <h6>CDC/FHI Ahni HIV/Aids prevention among youths - PEP<h6>\r\n        <p>In August - September, 2012, Jakin collaborated with FHI Ahni to implement HIV/Aids prevention peer education plus strategy in Mainland LG.107 peer educators were selected and intensively trained.They reached 1,500 youths with HIV/aids prevention message focusing on abstinence. A community awareness using road show was also conducted for the youths.</p>\r\n        <h6>SFH/Global Fund Malaria Round 8/AMFm project - Malaria community social sensitisation outreaches</h6>\r\n        <p>In November - December, 2012, Jakin conducted Malaria community social sensitisation outreaches using drama presentation in 8 Mainland LG communities and 7 communities in Shomolu LG under the SFH Global Fund Malaria Round 8/AMFm project. 1, 281 community members were reached Mainland and over 1100 in Shomolu.</p>\r\n        <h6>FHI/AHNI - PMTCT &amp; HCT community mobilization outreaches</h6>\r\n        <p>In June  November, 2012, JAKIN N.G.O conducted nine (9) FHI/AHNI funded PMTCT &amp; HCT community mobilization outreaches in Twenty (20) communities within Yaba LCDA. 753 community members especially pregnant women and nursing mothers were reached with I.E.C materials distribution, town crying, person to person discussions and focus group discussions.</p>\r\n        <h6>FHI/Ahni - Youth community awareness outreaches on HIV/Aids prevention &amp; sexual reproductive health </h6>\r\n        <p>In 2012, August - November, JAKIN N.G.O collaborated with FHI/AHNI to conduct 8 Youth community awareness outreaches on HIV/Aids prevention &amp; sexual reproductive health in eight<strong> </strong>communities within Mainland LGA. </p>\r\n        <p>Six hundred and fourteen in and out of school youths were reached with I.E.C materials distribution, play lets and focus group discussions.</p>\r\n        <h6>LSMOH/ACOMIN Monitoring of role model care giver on malaria</h6>\r\n        <p>In collaboration with the Lagos State Ministry of Health and the Association of CSOs on Malaria Immunization and Nutrition (ACOMIN),</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '1016', 9, 'Donor-Funded-Projects', '', '0'),
(7, 0, '2013-06-14 10:13:56', '', '', 0, '<p>Mrs Irenbo E. and her 4 years old son Paul were introduced to JAKIN N.G.O through a friend who has at sometime benefited from our charity programs.        </p>\r\n        <p>Before now, Paul Irenbo was diagnosed of hernia but due to lack of finance his mother could not afford an hospital medication, hence Paul&rsquo;s condition deteriorated.        </p>\r\n        <p>Mrs Irenbo E. met with JAKIN N.G.O and thereafter the organization arranged for Paul&rsquo;s surgery and paid for all medical expenses. The organization also made cash donations to Paul and the mother during and after the surgery.        </p>\r\n        <p>Knowing that for Paul&rsquo;s mother to conveniently take care of him, she must have a source of income; this the organization put into consideration and then decided to build a kiosk for her, there after empowered her in retail business of food stuff.        </p>\r\n        <p>Today, Mrs Irenbo E. conveniently fends for a healthy Paul and her entire family. Thanks to God and JAKIN N.G.O!!!!!</p>', '1017', 13, 'Success-Stories', 'Mrs Irenbo E', '0'),
