(34, 0, '2013-09-25 13:55:54', '', '', 5, '<h6>WRONG USE OF AGBO KULA KULA</h6>\r\n  <p>Medicines are substances used<strong> </strong>in preventing, curing or alleviating diseases or pain. It comes in tablets or syrup.Examples are paracetamols, panadols, cough syrup, vitamin c amongst others.<br>\r\n   Wrong use of medicines refers to the wrong prescription, overdose, under dose, and misuse of drugs. They take the forms of</p>\r\n  <p>Not taking the correct dose.</p>\r\n  <p>Not taking them at the right time.</p>\r\n  <p>Swallowing amala, eba or fufu with medicine inside.</p>\r\n  <p>Grinding the medicine into powder and pouring inside drink or water.</p>\r\n  <p>Buying unprescribed medicines.</p>\r\n  <p>Self administration.</p>\r\n  <h6><strong>EFFECTS OF THE WRONG USE OF MEDICINES.</strong></h6>\r\n  <p><strong>Antimicrobial resistance. </strong>The body can get so used to the medicine or may not need any treatment at that time.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Prolonged illness.</strong> The illness may be prolonged up to the extent of being admitted in the hospital.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Death. </strong>Mysterious deaths can occur.</p>\r\n  <h6><strong>REASONS FOR THE WRONG USE OF DRUGS.</strong></h6>\r\n  <p>Lack of skills and knowledge.</p>\r\n  <p>Hospital phobia.</p>\r\n  <p>Suggestions from people around.</p>\r\n  <p>Trying to avoid hospital protocols.</p>\r\n  <p>Economizing resources.</p>\r\n  <h6><strong>CONCLUSION</strong></h6>\r\n  <p>Do not buy over the counter drugs.</p>\r\n  <p>Do not patronize road side drug vendors.</p>\r\n  <p>Take the correct dose of medicine at the correct time.</p>\r\n  <p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\Visit the doctor whenever you fall sick.</p>\r\n<h6></h6>', '1043_1380116950', 27, 'Wrong-Use-of-Medicines', 'WRONG USE OF AGBO', '0'),
(36, 0, '2013-09-25 13:59:34', '', '', 5, '<h6>FACTS ABOUT CANCER</h6>\r\n    <p>Those who sleep less than six hours a night are more likely to develop colon cancer than those who sleep more. One in eight deaths in the world are due to cancer. Cancer causes more deaths than AIDS, tuberculosis, and malaria combined. Lung, prostate, and stomach cancers are the most commonly diagnosed cancers in men. Breast, cervix, and colorectal cancers are the most commonly diagnosed cancers in women. Cancer is not just one disease; rather it is a set of diseases. Different agents cause each type of cancer. Researchers believe that more than half of all cancers and cancer deaths are potentially preventable. There are 28 million cancer survivors worldwide. Poor dental hygiene can cause gingivitis, an inflammation of the gums. Over time, high levels of inflammation in the body can increase a persons risk of developing cancer. </p>\r\n    <h6> <strong>TYPES OF CANCER</strong></h6>\r\n    <p>Cancer can typically affect every organ of the body and spread the disease by destroying the neighbouring cells. The various cancers are named typically after the place where they originate in the body. For example, Breast cancer is cancer that originates in the cells of the breast. With about more than 100 types of cancer, this class of diseases is divided into five broad categories.<br>\r\n     Cancer that originates in the skin or in the tissues that cover the internal organs is known as Carcinoma. Cancer that starts in the bone, fat muscle, cartilage or blood vessels are known as Sarcoma. Cancer in the blood forming tissues like the bone marrow is known as Leukemia. This type of cancer enters the blood stream and spreads to all the parts of the body. Cancer that begins in the immune system of the body is known as Lymphoma and Myeloma. Cancer in the cells of the brain and spinal cord are known as Central nervous system cancer. </p>\r\n    <h6> <strong>TIPS ON HOW TO PREVENT CANCER</strong></h6>\r\n    <p>Reduce the intake of red meat and animal fat.</p>\r\n    <p>Reduce the intake of alcohol.</p>\r\n    <p>Eat fruits and vegetables e.g cabbage.</p>\r\n    <p>Avoid smoking and exposure to smoke.</p>\r\n    <p>Practice safe sex to prevent cervical cancer.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>NOTE</strong>: HIV\\\\ AIDS is associated with various kinds of cancer.</p>', '1045_1380117546', 27, 'Facts-About-Cancer', 'Facts About Cancer', '0'),
(37, 0, '2013-09-25 14:05:07', '', '', 5, '<h6><strong>WHAT IS GENDER</strong></h6>\r\n    <p>Gender is simply the societal roles assigned to male or female in any community. It is what the society expects of men and women or girls and boys.</p>\r\n    <p>Lets ask ourselves- <strong>what areas are girls superior to boys or boys to girls?</strong><br>\r\n     The simple answer is we are all equal.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>Gender equality simply means:</strong></p>\r\n    <p>Sisters been treated the way our brothers are treated.</p>\r\n    <p>It is when our parents do not have favorite among us thier children.</p>\r\n    <p>We the Girls should not be preferred to our brothers and our brothers not preferred to us the girls.</p>\r\n    <p>It means when you assign us different domestic tasks not minding whether we are boys or girls.</p>\r\n    <h6><strong>GENDER EQUALITY AT HOME.</strong></h6>\r\n    <p>Boys should take part in doing domestic works like cooking, washing plates, washing cars and sweeping.</p>\r\n    <p>Boys and we girls alike should be enrolled in schools.</p>\r\n    <p>There should be respect for the senior child whether girl or boy.</p>\r\n    <p>Males should not administer any form of violence against females for example: Daddy physically abusing Mummy or brothers, uncles, step fathers and even Daddies sexually or physically abusing the girls.</p>\r\n    <p>Daddies and mummies should be given equal respect.</p>\r\n    <p>Our biological difference of being male and female should not be used as a yardstick to say females are weaker so they are inferior to males.    </p>\r\n    <h6><strong>GENDER EQUALITY IN THE SCHOOL.</strong></h6>\r\n    <p>There should not be any form of prejudice in the sitting arrangements in the classroom</p>\r\n    <p>Our teachers should not show any form of dislike to the pupils\\\\students based on their sex.</p>\r\n    <p>We the girls can also do sciences and become pilots, engineers and technicians if we wish.</p>\r\n    <p>Boys too should also be encouraged to do arts or social science subjects like home economics, home management and even nursing.</p>\r\n    <p>Both males and females should be given equal task in the school not the girls do the cleaning and the boys do the cutting of grass.</p>\r\n    <p>Both male and female should be given equal opportunity to participate in all sports.</p>\r\n    <p>Both males and females should be given equal opportunity to represent the school.</p>\r\n    <p>Both male and females should be given equal leadership rights.</p>\r\n    <p>Male teachers should desist from giving personal tasks to female students and vice versa.</p>\r\n    <p>Both male and female teachers should be given equal opportunities within and outside the school.</p>\r\n    <p>Violence against females both students and teachers by males should be prohibited.<strong></strong></p>\r\n    <h6><strong>GENDER EQUALITY IN THE SOCIETY.</strong></h6>\r\n    <p>Girls and women should exercise their rights as much as the boys and men do.</p>\r\n    <p>The public should avoid seeing leadership positions as fit for only the men. Women can also be leaders e.g. Presidents, Governors e.t.c.</p>\r\n    <p>Girls and women should be seen and not only heard.</p>\r\n    <p>Men and boys should desist from considering themselves as the ones who have the final say.</p>\r\n    <p>Both males and females should be given equal rights to vote and be voted for.</p>\r\n    <p>There must be zero tolerance to violence against women and girls.</p>\r\n    <p>Both sons and daughters should be given equal rights to their parents inheritance.</p>\r\n    <p>Females should not be seen as household objects that should be confined to the home.</p>\r\n    <p>Females should be seen to have more value than been house keepers and baby bearers.</p>\r\n    <p>We need to say NO to cultures and practices that relegate females!</p>\r\n    <p><strong>To our parents:</strong></p>\r\n    <p>Household tasks should be allocated to both girls and boys equally.</p>\r\n    <p>Do not prefer boys to girls or vice versa.</p>\r\n    <p>Let the boys and girls know that they have equal rights in the home and society at large.</p>\r\n    <p>Do not show favoritism in enrolling your wards in school.</p>\r\n    <p>Give both girls and boys equal rights to be heard in the home.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>To my fellow JAKIN CHILDRENS CLUB members.</strong></p>\r\n    <p>Respect each other because respect is reciprocal.</p>\r\n    <p>Boys should not neglect girls and girls should not do same to boys.</p>\r\n    <p>There is no vocation or profession designed for girls or boys alone.</p>\r\n    <p>Everyone has the right of fair hearing.</p>\r\n    <p>Everyone should be given equal chances in the home, school and society.</p>\r\n    <p>There should be equal representation of girls and women in every sector of the society.</p>\r\n    <p>Boys should desist from any violence against the girls.</p>\r\n    <p>Boys speak up against any culture, tradition or norm that relegates or abuse the females.</p>\r\n    <br>\r\n    <p>TOGETHER WE CAN SAVE OUR FUTURE!</p>', '1046_1380117574', 27, 'Presentation-on-Gender-Equality', 'Presentation on Gender Equality', '0'),
(38, 0, '2013-09-25 14:52:27', '', '', 5, ' <p>I was in Nigeria on a UNICEF mission April 8-18. A heightened interest in Africa, due to the Tokyo International Conference on African Development set for Yokohama in June, where African leaders will discuss the continent&rsquo;s development, prompted UNICEF to dispatch me to the region&rsquo;s most populous country: Nigeria.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Nigeria is about 2.5 times the size of Japan. Its growing population is about 162.5 million, 49 percent of which is below age 18. The average number of children a woman gives birth to in her lifetime is about 5.5.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Nigeria ranks seventh among OPEC member nations in terms of crude oil production. At a glance it is a country of wealth and potential, both in terms of natural resources and human resources.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>However, Nigeria is a country of contradictions and unsolved challenges. About 70 percent of its people lead a shoestring existence on less than a 125 yen a day, and about 40 percent of children under 5 suffer from growth retardation</span>. Only some 60 percent of children attend primary school and only about 20 percent go on to junior secondary school. Nearly 40 percent of the population cannot read or write.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>When I arrived in Lagos, Nigeria&rsquo;s largest city, it was boiling hot. The city&rsquo;s population is said to stand at 16 million today, and is projected to increase to 25 million in three years.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>People from neighboring countries and other Nigerian states flood into Lagos for a better life. Yet, what I saw was a cluster of skyscrapers and plenty of slums. According to a UNICEF staff in Lagos, some 70 percent of the people live in over 100 slums spread around the city.</p>\r\n\r\n        <div id="attachment_4927"><a href="http://awd-data.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/20130519_agnes_nigeria_3.jpg"><img src="http://awd-data.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/20130519_agnes_nigeria_3.jpg" width="300" height="182"></a>\r\n\r\n          <p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n        <p>Infrastructure is failing with frequent blackouts, no running water and no functioning sewagesystem. Trash is left on streets, rivers and beaches. When the rainy season arrives, floods are common.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Adding to the misery, Lagos is said to be one of the world&rsquo;s most dangerous cities, with frequent robberies, kidnappings and carjackings.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>The average monthly salary of a primary school teacher is about 20,000 naira, or 12,800 yen. But Lagos is an ex pensive city, where some products can be as expensive as in Tokyo. How do people survive? No wonder the crime rate is high.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Macoco is a slum built right on the water where mostly fishermen live. The water is blackened with refuse and garbage floating on its surface. Stagnant pools of water bubble with human waste. Houses built over the water threaten to fall apart at the smallest provocation. Children romp around, splashing in the dirt and water barefoot.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Only 20 percent of children go to school in Makoko. The closest public school is an hour&rsquo;s walk and classes are so full that some have as many as 180 students in one classroom. No toilets, no running water, no electricity, no windowpanes, no books, no lunch and not enough teachers are just a few of the problems they face.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>The children of Macoco stay home because their parents need them to help out on the boats or clean and smoke fish and sell it in the markets. The odor and smoke in the slum makes people cough and rub their bloodshot eyes.        </p>\r\n\r\n        <div id="attachment_4929"><a href="http://awd-data.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/20130519_agnes_nigeria_5.jpg"><img  src="http://awd-data.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/20130519_agnes_nigeria_5.jpg" width="300" height="210"></a>\r\n\r\n          <p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n        <p>Jakin, an NGO that operates in the area, addresses malaria, tuberculosis and HIV/AIDS as its main concerns. Besides helping with health issues, it also helps children and widows. It sends children to school, helps educate young people and loans money to women to start their own businesses.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Dustbin is another slum we visited. It is built on a huge garbage dump. I thought the living conditions of Macoco were bad, but Dustbin is even worse. Most of the people who live there have nowhere else to go. Due to a lack of jobs and support, they ended up in a garbage dump. A family I visited had been living there for 18 years. Social mobility exists, but only for a few. The rich get richer, while the poor get poorer.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Lagos is said to have 100,000 street children. I met some of them in shelters and many on the streets. Oshodi is a busy area where markets and buses crowd the streets. Trafficked children, runaway children and children who lost their parents sleep on the streets of Oshodi. Mud and dirt serve as their bedding. Between 8 and 18 years old, they fall victim to gangs, and girls are often sexually abused by boys and men on the streets. NGOs and local leaders try to help, but the staggering number of children makes their work endless.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>I visited shelters for boys and listened to their life stories. Some were driven away from their homes because of poverty, others escaped from abuse. The girls&rsquo; stories are even sadder, as most have been drugged, sexually abused, raped and impregnated. At the shelters they either go to school or learn trades so they can become independent.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>When we asked why such a disparity of wealth exists, people often cited corruption as the cause.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>&ldquo;Resources are plentiful but not equally distributed. Oil money flows only between big shots and the government,&rdquo; a young journalist said.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>UNICEF believes there must be a way to attain equity, at least for public services that benefit children. The organization, along with Lagos&rsquo; municipal government, conducted surveys to find children who were unaccounted for and to determine the sources of the many problems.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>These results prompted the Lagos government to respond, and many projects have been launched in the public health sector. UNICEF also initiated the establishment of Child Protection Networks involving NGOs, government agencies and legal and medical centers. All 36 provinces in Nigeria now have their own CPN and the networks are making great progress in protecting children.</p>\r\n\r\n        <div id="attachment_4928"><a href="http://awd-data.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/20130519_agnes_nigeria_4.jpg"><img alt="" src="http://awd-data.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/20130519_agnes_nigeria_4.jpg" width="300" height="196"></a>\r\n\r\n          <p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n        <p>However sad the situation is, Nigerians that I met were warm and positive people. Poverty makes life hard, but many of them are hopeful. I truly believe that with the right approach, Nigeria and other African countries will become the engine of growth for the world.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>UNICEF uses the word &ldquo;ownership&rdquo; to describe its approach: This means that the people of Nigeria must not only feel that they are part of the problem, but they are also part of the solution.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Agencies like UNICEF will continue to help as a partner for change, not as a benefactor. The organization provides expertise, but everyone has to do their part to make things work and be responsible for the outcomes. If we can succeed in Nigeria, it will be an example for the rest of Africa.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>I hope discussions at TICAD in Yokohama next month will focus not only on commercial investment, but on investment in the potential of children. A well-educated and healthy population in a safe and clean environment is a prerequisite for successful investment. Africa still has a way to go to get there, but it will, if everyone acknowledges the challenges and lends a helping hand.</p>\r\n\r\n        <br />\r\n\r\n        <i>This article was culled from asahiweekly.com</i> ....</div><br>', '1048_1380120717', 27, 'Agnes-Chans-Visit-to-Nigeria', 'Agnes Chan\\''s Visit to Nigeria', '0'),
