(62, 0, '2014-04-22 13:09:23', '', 'n_1072_1398171911_1398172163', 1, '<p>An initiative of JAKIN which is established to identify challenges needy people are facing, discover the source and improvise lasting ways of improving their physical, social and financial conditions. Since its inception in February 2004 till date SPP has supported over 10,000 less privileged people in Nigeria and as far as Sudan- Darfur, Liberia and Ghana. The project focuses on the provision of psychosocial, home visit, general health, welfare, educational and economic empowerment support.</p><p>On a daily basis through SPP, health related issues such as minor surgeries, hospital bills, blood transfusion bills and prescribed drugs are addressed. Nutritional, transportation, clothing, accommodation and personal hygiene support is also made available to beneficiaries. Educational challenges are also met through provision of public school enrolment and completion support to vulnerable children. This supports includes provision of basic school items, career talks, transport fare & lunch break support, advocacy to schools to seek admission, school visits, caregiver counseling, student counseling, payment of afterschool and summer lesson fees. We also provide awareness, care and support on various social ills especially drug abuse, communicable diseases, sexual abuse and gender based violence to schools.</p><p>Entrepreneurship support is also provided for individuals and families through vocational skill trainings, business management training, mentorship, provision of business or skill equipments and setting up of numerous retails businesses. </p><p>Community and individual disaster victims are not left out as relief materials and counseling supports are provided for them. Prisoners, physically challenged people and street people are also reached with various forms of supports to mitigate their problems.</p><p>The target beneficiaries of the project are vulnerable children, women, youths, men and families and it funded mainly by kindhearted individuals, organizations, groups and churches.</p>', '1072_1398171911', 8, 'Samaritan-Platform-Project-SPP', 'Samaritan Platform Project (SPP)', '0'),
(63, 0, '2014-04-22 13:11:19', '', 'n_1073_1398172192_1398172279', 1, '<p>On March 13th, 2010, the N.G.O inaugurated the JAKIN Childrens Club (JCC) for street orphans and vulnerable children with 30 members, as at today, the club has a membership of over 400.</p><p>The club brings VCs together once a month to receive reformative and transformative trainings in a well structured environment to help improve their quality of life. Participants are refreshed, given transport fare allowance, and receive take home packages of nutritional, educational or hygiene supports. Members have enjoyed excursions, nutrition, sports, health, career, road safety and also child rights trainings among others.</p>', '1073_1398172192', 8, 'JAKIN-CHILDRENS-CLUB-FOR-VULNERABLE-CHILDREN', 'JAKIN CHILDRENS CLUB (FOR VULNERABLE CHILDREN)', '0'),
(64, 0, '2014-04-22 13:29:33', '', 'n_1074_1398173268_1398173373', 1, '<p><span style=\\"color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Verb, \\''Helvetica Neue\\'', Helvetica, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22.399999618530273px;\\">Since the inauguration of Jakin Childrens Club in March 2010, JAKIN N.G.O celebrates the May 27th annual International Childrens day with members of the club. The event is held to give vulnerable children a reason to celebrate childhood. They are brought together as a family to enjoy various games, refreshment, dance and performances both guest artists and also members of the club. The event has been growing in leaps and bounds since it commenced in 2010 with 32 children who went home with stationery gift packs comprising of a branded pencil case with SAY NO TO TUBERCULOSIS inscribed on it, pencil, biro, sharpener, eraser and an exercise book. The event was also used to mark the annual International TB Day.</span><br style=\\"color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Verb, \\''Helvetica Neue\\'', Helvetica, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22.399999618530273px;\\"><span style=\\"color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Verb, \\''Helvetica Neue\\'', Helvetica, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22.399999618530273px;\\">The 2011 edition had 174 (95 females, 79 males) children in attendance and each received hygiene packs containing sponge, toothpaste, toothbrush, bathing soap, washing soap and body cream. In 2012, 200 (108 females, 92 females) children benefitted as each child received a gift pack containing a branded tea-cup, milk, chocolate, biscuits and Indomie noodles. The 2013 edition proofed the amazing impact this event is having on its beneficiaries and also the growth of JCC, it had in attendance, 310 (151 male and 159 female) children. The children were strategically lined up for collection of the party gifts, which contained 4 indomie noodles, 1 bathing soap, 1 exercise book and 1 washing soap each.</span><br></p>', '1074_1398173268', 8, 'Annual-Childrens-Day-Celebration', 'Annual Children\\''s Day Celebration', '0');
